commentBody: I didn’t want Kamala Harris to win because Stacey Abrams, who is far more inspiring, and more qualified, should be the first Africa-American woman president.  She’s the real deal.

After the first debate in June, many commentators talked about strong Harris performance.  I thought otherwise.  Either Ms. Harris supported federally mandated busing (a losing proposition), or was just opportunistic and wanted to attack the front runner.  Yes, she got a bump in the polls, but the polls did not show how much support she lost at the same time.  There is a reason two late septuagenarians are leading the national polls.  People believe they both care about persons like them.

Well, I'd say, "All of the above; that about sums it up." Women get held to way higher/different standards. That is part of the reason Hillary Clinton was labeled as "unapproachable" or "not genuine". How can you be genuine when you get criticized for every single thing you say and do (e.g., "bake cookies" comment vs. being appointed to fix health care, for examples from opposite ends of the spectrum)? Walk that line? Who can even see that line? 

But I agree, Harris and her campaign also made a lot of mistakes.
Kamala had my support from the beginning, but over time it was evident that she had neither a compelling vision nor a clear message. It's difficult to support a void.

One of the most qualities I appreciate in a politician - or anyone - is that person's ability to grow, to admit mistakes and apologize for those. This should of course be a natural part of growing up. But it isn't. Majority of Americans, including Kamala Harris, want people to come out of the womb with one point of view and never to defer from it. "I'm always right." (As in DJT). I prefer people/candidates who are willing to learn, to grow, to adopt different viewpoints, to apologize with willingness - in other words, to be human. That's why I like and support Joe Biden.

The Democrats' far-left wing has four explanations for everything that doesn't meet their expectations;  Racism;  Sexism;  Capitalism;  Climate change.

Does it ever occur to y'all that your proposed radical policies could be unpopular?

Nah.

commentBody:
What happened was that the Democratic Party has taken a primary strategy of throwing the sink at the wall in hope that something with corporate support will stick enough to oust Bernie. Kamala just didn't stick. Media support has moved to the sludgy trail of Buttigieg after every effort to prop up Biden thudded under the Hillary Coefficient which insists that America wants a milk toast centrist drenched in political baggage. 

If only there were an incredibly popular candidate whose campaign were funded entirely by individual contributors who speaks with an integrity that would turn Trump into salt. If the media gave Sanders the publicity platform offered to Biden the DNC would create an unstoppable Mechagodzilla of BernieMania. And yet the story we're told is that the party is in trouble. Something reeks of corruption and America's nose is keen to it. That's the trouble.
